<subSubSection id="C3776556ED1C3878FC9AFCB9FC66FC36" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDED1C3878FC9AFCB9FC66FC36" blockId="589.[810,1452,173,1866]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FC9AFCB9FC25FC50" bold="true" box="[863,992,887,913]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name is derived from the Greek 
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FCEFFC54FCA2FC72" box="[810,871,922,947]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">camp</emphasis>
(=caterpillar) and - 
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FBB5FC57FB03FC72" box="[1136,1222,921,947]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">delphys</emphasis>
, referring to the typically caterpillar-like body form of the genus. Gender masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556ED1C387BFC9AFC31FCC6FCC9" lastPageId="590" lastPageNumber="591" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDED1C3878FC9AFC31FB8FFB24" blockId="589.[810,1452,173,1866]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FC9AFC31FC09FBD8" bold="true" box="[863,972,1023,1049]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FC19FC31FB47FBD8" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[988,1154,1023,1049]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Campodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FC19FC31FB47FBD8" box="[988,1154,1023,1049]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Campodelphys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FB49FC31FB32FBD8" bold="true" box="[1164,1271,1023,1049]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4ED1C3878FB49FC31FB32FBD8" box="[1164,1271,1023,1049]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resembles both 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FCEFFBEFFC36FBFA" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[810,1011,1057,1083]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Procampodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FCEFFBEFFC36FBFA" box="[810,1011,1057,1083]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Procampodelphys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FBC4FBEFFBB7FBFA" bold="true" box="[1025,1138,1057,1083]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4ED1C3878FBC4FBEFFBB7FBFA" box="[1025,1138,1057,1083]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FB72FBEFFA93FBFA" authorityName="Chatton &amp; Brement" authorityYear="1911" box="[1207,1366,1057,1083]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Prophioseides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FB72FBEFFA93FBFA" box="[1207,1366,1057,1083]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Prophioseides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the body form of the adult female. 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FB6AFB8DFA8BFB9C" authorityName="Chatton &amp; Brement" authorityYear="1911" box="[1199,1358,1091,1117]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Prophioseides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FB6AFB8DFA8BFB9C" box="[1199,1358,1091,1117]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Prophioseides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be excluded from further detailed comparisons with the new genus because it has a denticulate coxal gnathobase on the mandible, whereas the new genus has a pectinate medial margin on the gnathobase
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDED1C3878FC9AFB20FB13F88B" blockId="589.[810,1452,173,1866]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
In 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FCBBFB23FBE1FAC6" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[894,1060,1261,1287]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Campodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FCBBFB23FBE1FAC6" box="[894,1060,1261,1287]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Campodelphys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FBE9FB23FB50FAC6" bold="true" box="[1068,1173,1261,1287]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4ED1C3878FBE9FB23FB50FAC6" box="[1068,1173,1261,1287]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
the swimming legs each have a 2-segmented exopod and a 1- or 2-segmented endopod, and both rami are broad and armed with thick, spiniform setae. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FBE0FA9DFB2BFAAC" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[1061,1262,1363,1389]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Procampodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FBE0FA9DFB2BFAAC" box="[1061,1262,1363,1389]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Procampodelphys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FAC4FA9DFAB3FAAC" bold="true" box="[1281,1398,1363,1389]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4ED1C3878FAC4FA9DFAB3FAAC" box="[1281,1398,1363,1389]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
the swimming legs are much reduced and narrow, with the unsegmented, lobate rami bearing fewer setae. In contrast to the relatively complex condition of the swimming legs, the mouthparts of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FB96FA15FB3CFA34" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[1107,1273,1499,1525]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Campodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FB96FA15FB3CFA34" box="[1107,1273,1499,1525]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Campodelphys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FACDFA12FABFFA37" bold="true" box="[1288,1402,1500,1526]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4ED1C3878FACDFA12FABFFA37" box="[1288,1402,1500,1526]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are much more reduced, with both the maxillule and maxilla represented by setose lobes and the maxilliped is armed only with 1 or 2 setae. These differences serve to clearly differentiate between members of these two genera. In the form of the swimming legs, 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FB51F94BFAFFF95E" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[1172,1338,1669,1695]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Campodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FB51F94BFAFFF95E" box="[1172,1338,1669,1695]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Campodelphys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FA87F948FA6EF961" bold="true" box="[1346,1451,1670,1696]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4ED1C3878FA87F948FA6EF961" box="[1346,1451,1670,1696]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
more closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FB81F969FAF9F903" authority="Illg, 1958" authorityName="Illg" authorityYear="1958" box="[1092,1340,1703,1730]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Scolecodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FB81F969FB05F900" box="[1092,1216,1703,1729]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Scolecodes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CED1C3878FB0EF969FAF9F903" author="Illg" box="[1227,1340,1703,1730]" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the United States National Museum" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" pagination="463 - 649" part="107" refId="ref328917" refString="Illg, P. L. (1958) North American copepods of the family Notodelphyidae. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 107 (3390), 463 - 649. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.108 - 3390.463" title="North American copepods of the family Notodelphyidae" type="journal article" year="1958">Illg, 1958</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
than any other genus, although these two genera can be easily distinguished by a range of other characters. The five species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED1C3878FC65F8C3FB83F8E6" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[928,1094,1805,1831]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Campodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FC65F8C3FB83F8E6" box="[928,1094,1805,1831]" italics="true" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">Campodelphys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFED1C3878FB88F8C0FB73F8E9" bold="true" box="[1101,1206,1806,1832]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4ED1C3878FB88F8C0FB73F8E9" box="[1101,1206,1806,1832]" pageId="589" pageNumber="590" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
described below may be distinguished by the following key.
</paragraph>
